# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: braybrook-victoria
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The **2021 Australian census**, simply called the **2021 Census**, was the eighteenth national Census of Population and Housing in Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The 2021 Census took place on 10 August 2021, and was conducted by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] It had a response rate of 96.1%, up from the 95.1% at the 2016 census.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The total population of the Commonwealth of Australia was counted as 25,422,788, an increase of 8.6 per cent or 2,020,896 people over the previous 2016 census.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Results from the 2021 census were released to the public on 28 June 2022 from the Australian Bureau of Statistics website.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] A small amount of additional 2021 census data was released in October 2022 and in 2023.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Australia's next census is scheduled to take place in 2026.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The census was undertaken during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] It therefore provided a clear snapshot of how the pandemic impacted Australian society.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] In Australia, completing the census is compulsory for all people in Australia on census night, only excluding foreign diplomats and their families.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Census data is used to "help governments, businesses, not-for-profit and community organisations across the country make informed decisions", including helping governments to plan the provision of services.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] An independent report from Lateral Economics found that for every $1 of investment on the census, $6 of benefits are created in the Australian economy.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Since the 2001 Census, all households have the option of allowing their census data, including personal information such as names and addresses, to be stored by the National Archives of Australia (NAA) for 99 years.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] 99 years after Census Night, the NAA will release that data to the public in a Census Time Capsule.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Censuses stored by the NAA cannot by accessed, amended, or retrieved by anyone, including courts and tribunal, until their release, the first of which will occur in 2100.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The 2020 Census Test occurred on 27 October 2020 with around 100,000 households from Sydney, Adelaide, Darwin, and Canberra, as well as communities in Karratha, Warrnambool, and Alice Springs Town Camps.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Every census, the ABS makes a recommendation to the Australian Government on the topics to be included, based on the benefit that data would provide to Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Through the *Census and Statistics Amendment (Statistical Information) Regulations 2020*, the federal parliament approves topics that may be included.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] For the 2021 census, the ABS had been authorised to include questions relating to long-term health conditions and service in the Australian Defence Force, and would not continue asking questions about home internet access considering the rise of mobile devices.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] This represented the first significant change to census topics since 2006.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Through late 2017, the ABS began discussions with major census data users on what was needed.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] From 3 April to 30 June 2018, a formal consultation process occurred on the online "ABS Consultation Hub", with the ABS receiving 450 submissions, 315 of which were published with consent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Since 2006, the ABS has allowed the census to be completed online, moving in 2016 to be digital-first.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Like 2016, the 2021 Census was primarily collected online, with paper census forms being available on request for any household.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] In 2016, around a third of all households requested and completed their census using the paper form.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] The population counts for Australian states and territories were that New South Wales remains the most populous state, with 8,072,163 people counted, ahead of Victoria (6,503,491) and Queensland (5,156,138).
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Of all residents over two-thirds (72.4% or 18,235,690) were born in Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] Over a quarter of the population (27.6% or 7,502,450 persons) said they were born overseas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] After Australia, England is the most common birthplace with 927,490 people.
[src:braybrook-victoria/2021-australian-census] India became the third-largest country of birth, surpassing China and New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The **Australian Bureau of Statistics** (**ABS**) is an agency of the Australian Government that collates and analyses statistical data on economic, demographic, environmental and social issues to support policy research and development.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The bureau's function originated in the Commonwealth Bureau of Census and Statistics, established in 1905, four years after the Federation of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The organisation took on its present name in 1975.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS conducts Australia's Census of Population and Housing every five years and publishes its findings online.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Efforts to count the population of Australia started in 1795 with "musters" that involved physically gathering a community to be counted, a practice that continued until 1825.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The first colonial censuses were conducted in New South Wales in 1828; in Tasmania in 1841; South Australia in 1844; Western Australia in 1848; and Victoria in 1854.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Each colony continued to collect statistics separately despite attempts to coordinate collections through an annual Conference of Statisticians.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The first simultaneous census across all the Australian colonies occurred in 1881.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] A national statistical office was subsequently proposed to develop comparable statistics.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The Commonwealth Bureau of Census and Statistics (CBCS) was established under the *Census and Statistics Act 1905*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Sir George Handley Knibbs was appointed as the first Commonwealth Statistician.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The bureau was located in Melbourne – at that time the temporary seat of federal government – attached to the Department of Home Affairs.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In 1928, the bureau relocated to Canberra, where in 1932 it was subsumed within the Department of the Treasury.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The first national census, which deployed about 7300 collectors, occurred in 1911.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Although coordination and data sharing were facilitated by CBCS, each state in Australia initially had its own statistical office and worked with the CBCS to produce national data.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Some states faced challenges in providing a satisfactory statistical service through their own offices, resulting in mergers with the CBCS.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The Tasmanian Statistical Office was transferred to the CBCS in 1924, and the New South Wales Bureau of Statistics amalgamated into it in 1957.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The final unification of all state statistical offices with the CBCS occurred in the late 1950s under the guidance of Sir Stanley Carver, who was the New South Wales Statistician acting as the Commonwealth Statistician.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In 1974, the CBCS was abolished and replaced by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The *Australian Bureau of Statistics Act 1975* established the ABS as a statutory authority headed by the Australian Statistician, who reported to the federal Treasurer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In 2015, the Australian Government announced a $250 million five-year investment in the ABS to modernise its systems and processes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Once every 5 years, the ABS conducts the Australian Census of Population and Housing as stipulated under federal law in the Constitution of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The most recent was conducted on 10 August 2021.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Statistics from the census were published on the ABS website in June 2022.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The census aims to accurately measure the population, number of dwellings in Australia, and a range of their key characteristics.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Census data is used for defining electoral boundaries, planning infrastructure, establishing community services, and formulating public policy.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In 2016, the ABS conducted its census largely online through its website and logins rather than through paper forms.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The bureau took the form offline for 43 hours from 8:09 pm on 9 August until 2:29 pm on 11 August.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] A comprehensive review by Alastair MacGibbon, Special Adviser to the Prime Minister on Cyber Security, tabled in October, concluded that five distributed denial-of-service attacks – in which incoming traffic from many different sources "floods" the site – had occurred.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] They had been much smaller than attacks experienced by other Australian Government websites and the preventable outages had resulted from a failed geoblocking strategy, compounded by a hardware failure when the contractor, IBM, attempted to reboot the system after the fourth attack.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] There was no indication that the census data was insecure or was compromised.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] A Senate inquiry was held into the 2016 census, reporting in November and making 16 recommendations including externally conducted privacy impact assessments, engagement with the non-government sector, reporting breaches of census-related data, open tendering, and stability in funding the bureau.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] An independent panel was also established by the Australian Statistician to help to ensure the quality of the 2016 census.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The 2021 census was conducted during the height of the global COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In obtaining data from 10,852,208 dwellings, it exceeded the ABS target.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The dwelling response rate was 96.1%, an increase from 95.1% in 2016.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS publishes monthly and quarterly economic information spanning interest rates, property prices, employment, the value of the Australian dollar, and commodity prices.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Publications include things such as: the Key Economic Indicators, Consumer Price Index, Australian National Accounts, Average Weekly Earnings, and Labour Force.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] In August 2017, the Treasurer issued a directive to the ABS to undertake a statistical collection into the views of Australians on the electoral roll about same-sex marriage.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] This is now referred to as the Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS previously published the *Yearbook Australia*, from 1908 to 2012 under various ISSNs and titles (*Commonwealth yearbook*, *Official yearbook of the Commonwealth of Australia*).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS publishes an annual report with a detailed description of the bureau's activities during the preceding year, accounting for its use of public resources and performance against planned outcomes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS maintains the Australian Statistical Geography Standard (ASGS), a system of geographic statistical areas in Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ASGS includes geographic structures created and maintained by the ABS, as well as structures defined by other bodies but which the ABS uses for reporting statistical information.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS structures within the ASGS include a Main Structure, which is a nested hierarchy of geographic areas ranging from very small units to the whole of Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] There are other ABS structures that are schemes with specific uses.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] They are built from units of the Main Structure, or smaller units in the same structure.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Examples include the Indigenous Structure, a structure for urban areas, and the Remoteness Structure.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The non-ABS structures within the ASGS have geographical units whose boundaries are defined by bodies such as state governments, and that may or may not cover the whole of Australia without gaps or overlaps.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Examples include electoral divisions, Postal Areas, and Suburbs and Localities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The boundaries of these units are approximated in the ASGS so they match boundaries in the ABS Main Structure.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The current version of the ASGS is Version 3 of 2021.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] These structures within the ASGS are defined by the ABS.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] These structures are defined by bodies other than the ABS, though the ABS commits to providing a range of statistics for them.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Where the legal or other boundaries of the geographical units within these structures don't exactly match mesh blocks boundaries, the ABS uses mesh block boundaries to approximate them; therefore the ASGS units should only be used for statistical purposes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ASGS was introduced by the ABS in 2011 as a replacement for the Australian Standard Geographical Classification (ASGC).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] New editions essentially coincide with the 5-yearly ABS censuses, though boundary changes made to Non-ABS structures may be updated as often as annually.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] After a consultation process, the ABS released details of its planned changes to the ASGS for Edition 4 (2026).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS has a partnership with DFAT to deliver statistical and institutional capability building programs for the Indo-Pacific region, both in-country and by hosting development visits.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The ABS has also hosted international development and study visits from countries including China, Japan, Canada, Korea, and Nepal.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Since 1975, the head of the ABS has been known as the "Australian Statistician".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The title has been previously known as the "Commonwealth Statistician".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] The incumbent since 11 December 2019 is David Gruen.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Previous incumbents have included David Kalisch and Brian Pink.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-bureau-of-statistics] Ian Ewing acted in the role from 13 January to 14 February 2014, and Jonathan Palmer acted from 17 February to 12 December 2014.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] During general play, players may position themselves anywhere on the field and use any part of their bodies to move the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The primary methods are kicking, handballing, and running with the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There are rules on how the ball can be handled; for example, players running with the ball must intermittently bounce or touch it on the ground.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Throwing the ball is not allowed, and players must not get caught holding the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A distinctive feature of the game is the mark, where players anywhere on the field who catch the ball from a kick (with specific conditions) are awarded unimpeded possession.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Possession of the ball is in dispute at all times except when a free kick or mark is paid.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Players can tackle using their hands or use their whole body to obstruct opponents.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Dangerous physical contact (such as pushing an opponent in the back), interference when marking, and deliberately slowing the play are discouraged with free kicks, distance penalties, or suspension for a certain number of matches depending on the severity of the infringement.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game features frequent physical contests, spectacular marking, fast movement of both players and the ball, and high scoring.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The sport's origins can be traced to football matches played in Melbourne, Victoria, in 1858, inspired by English public school football games.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Seeking to develop a game more suited to adults and Australian conditions, the Melbourne Football Club published the first laws of Australian football in May 1859.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian football has the highest spectator attendance of all sports in Australia while the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's only fully professional competition, is the nation's wealthiest sporting body.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The AFL Grand Final, held annually at the 100,000-capacity Melbourne Cricket Ground, is the highest-attended club championship event of any football code.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The sport is also played at amateur level in many countries and in several variations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Its rules are governed by the AFL Commission with the advice of the AFL's Laws of the Game Committee.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian football is known by several nicknames, including Australian rules football, Aussie rules, football and footy.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In some regions, where other codes of football are more popular, the sport is most often called AFL after the Australian Football League, while the league itself also uses this name for local competitions in some areas.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Primitive forms of football were played sporadically in the Australian colonies in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Compared to cricket and horse racing, football was considered a mere "amusement" by colonists at the time, and while little is known about these early one-off games, evidence does not support a causal link with Australian football.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In Melbourne, in 1858, in a move that would help to shape Australian football in its formative years, private schools (then termed "public schools" in accordance with nomenclature in England) began organising football games inspired by precedents at English public schools.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The earliest match, held on 15 June, was between Melbourne Grammar and St Kilda Grammar.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] On 10 July 1858, the Melbourne-based *Bell's Life in Victoria and Sporting Chronicle* published a letter by Tom Wills, captain of the Victoria cricket team, calling for the formation of a "foot-ball club" with a "code of laws" to keep cricketers fit during winter.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Born in Australia, Wills played a nascent form of rugby football while a pupil at Rugby School in England, and returned to his homeland a star athlete and cricketer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Two weeks later, Wills' friend, cricketer Jerry Bryant, posted an advertisement for a scratch match at the Richmond Paddock adjoining the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This was the first of several "kickabouts" held that year involving members of the Melbourne Cricket Club, including Wills, Bryant, W.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Trees were used as goalposts and play typically lasted an entire afternoon.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Without an agreed-upon code of laws, some players were guided by rules they had learned in the British Isles, "others by no rules at all".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Another milestone in 1858 was a 40-a-side match played under experimental rules between Melbourne Grammar and Scotch College, held at the Richmond Paddock.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Umpired by Wills and teacher John Macadam, it began on 7 August and continued over two subsequent Saturdays, ending in a draw with each side kicking one goal.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It is commemorated with a statue outside the MCG, and the two schools have since competed annually in the Cordner–Eggleston Cup, the world's oldest continuous football competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Since the 1920s, it has been suggested that Australian football may have been derived from the Irish sport of Gaelic football.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] However, there is no archival evidence in favour of a Gaelic influence, and the style of play shared between the two modern codes appeared in Australia long before the Irish game evolved in a similar direction.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Another theory, first proposed in 1983, posits that Wills, having grown up among Aboriginals in Victoria, may have seen or played the Aboriginal ball game of Marn Grook, and incorporated some of its features into early Australian football.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There is only circumstantial evidence that he knew of the game, and according to biographer Greg de Moore's research, Wills was "almost solely influenced by his experience at Rugby School".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A loosely organised Melbourne side, captained by Wills, played against other football enthusiasts in the winter and spring of 1858.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The following year, on 14 May, the Melbourne Football Club was officially established, making it one of the world's oldest football clubs.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Three days later, Wills, Hammersley, Thompson and teacher Thomas H.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Smith met near the MCG at the Parade Hotel, owned by Bryant, and drafted ten rules: "The Rules of the Melbourne Football Club".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] These are the laws from which Australian football evolved.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The club aimed to create a simple code suited to the hard playing surfaces around Melbourne, and to eliminate the roughest aspects of English school games—such as "hacking" (shin-kicking) in Rugby School football—to reduce the risk of injuries to working men.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In another significant departure from English public school football, the Melbourne rules omitted any offside law.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] "The new code was as much a reaction against the school games as influenced by them", writes Mark Pennings.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The rules were distributed throughout the colony; Thompson in particular did much to promote the new code in his capacity as a journalist.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Following Melbourne's lead, Geelong and Melbourne University also formed football clubs in 1859.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] While many early Victorian teams participated in one-off matches, most had not yet formed clubs for regular competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A South Yarra club devised its own rules.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] To ensure the supremacy of the Melbourne rules, the first club-level competition in Australia, the Caledonian Society's Challenge Cup (1861–64), stipulated that only the Melbourne rules were to be used.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This law was reinforced by the Athletic Sports Committee (ASC), which ran a variation of the Challenge Cup in 1865–66.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] With input from other clubs, the rules underwent several minor revisions, establishing a uniform code known as "Victorian rules".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1866, the "first distinctively Victorian rule", the running bounce, was formalised at a meeting of club delegates chaired by H.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Harrison, an influential pioneer who took up football in 1859 at the invitation of Wills, his cousin.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game around this time was defensive and low-scoring, played low to the ground in congested rugby-style scrimmages.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The typical match was a 20-per-side affair, played with a ball that was roughly spherical, and lasted until a team scored two goals.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The shape of the playing field was not standardised; matches often took place in rough, tree-spotted public parks, most notably the Richmond Paddock (Yarra Park), known colloquially as the Melbourne Football Ground.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Wills argued that the turf of cricket fields would benefit from being trampled upon by footballers in winter, and, as early as 1859, football was allowed on the MCG.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] However, cricket authorities frequently prohibited football on their grounds until the 1870s, when they saw an opportunity to capitalise on the sport's growing popularity.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Football gradually adapted to an oval-shaped field, and most grounds in Victoria expanded to accommodate the dual purpose—a situation that continues to this day.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Football became organised in South Australia in 1860 with the formation of the Adelaide Football Club, the oldest football club in Australia outside Victoria.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It devised its own rules, and, along with other Adelaide-based clubs, played a variety of codes until 1876, when they uniformly adopted most of the Victorian rules, with South Australian football pioneer Charles Kingston noting their similarity to "the old Adelaide rules".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Similarly, Tasmanian clubs quarrelled over different rules until they adopted a slightly modified version of the Victorian game in 1879.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The South Australian Football Association (SAFA), the sport's first governing body, formed on 30 April 1877, firmly establishing Victorian rules as the preferred code in that colony.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The Victorian Football Association (VFA) formed the following month.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Clubs began touring the colonies in the late 1870s, and in 1879 the first intercolonial match took place in Melbourne between Victoria and South Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1883, delegates representing the football associations of South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Queensland met to standardise the code across Australia.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Likewise, when New Zealand experienced a gold rush, the sport arrived with a rapid influx of Australian miners.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Now known as Australian rules or Australasian rules, the sport became the first football code to develop mass spectator appeal, attracting world record attendances for sports viewing and gaining a reputation as "the people's game".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian rules football reached Queensland and New South Wales as early as 1866; the sport experienced a period of dominance in the former, and in the latter, several regions remain strongholds of Australian rules, such as the Riverina.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] However, by the late 1880s, rugby football had become the dominant code in both colonies, as well as in New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This shift was largely due to rugby's spread with British migration, regional rivalries and the lack of strong local governing bodies.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the case of Sydney, denial of access to grounds, the influence of university headmasters from Britain who favoured rugby, and the loss of players to other codes inhibited the game's growth.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1896, delegates from six of the wealthiest VFA clubs—Carlton, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne and South Melbourne—met to discuss the formation of a breakaway professional competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Later joined by Collingwood and St Kilda, the clubs formed the Victorian Football League (VFL), which held its inaugural season in 1897.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The VFL's popularity grew rapidly as it made several innovations, such as instituting a finals system, reducing teams from 20 to 18 players, and introducing the behind as a score.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Richmond and University joined the VFL in 1908, and by 1925, with the addition of Hawthorn, Footscray and North Melbourne, it had become the preeminent league in the country and would take a leading role in many aspects of the sport.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The time around the federation of the Australian colonies in 1901 saw Australian rules undergo a revival in New South Wales, New Zealand and Queensland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1903, both the Queensland Australian Football League and the NSW Australian Football Association were established, and in New Zealand, as it moved towards becoming a dominion, leagues were also established in the major cities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This renewed popularity helped encourage the formation of the Australasian Football Council, which in 1908 in Melbourne staged the first national interstate competition, the Jubilee Australasian Football Carnival, with teams representing each state and New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game was also established early on in the new territories.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the new national capital Canberra both soccer and rugby had a head start, but following the first matches in 1911, Australian rules football in the Australian Capital Territory became a major participation sport.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] By 1981 it had become much neglected and quickly lagged behind the other football codes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian rules football in the Northern Territory began shortly after the outbreak of the war in 1916 with the first match in Darwin.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game went on to become the most popular sport in the Territory and build the highest participation rate for the sport nationally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Both World War I and World War II had a devastating effect on Australian football and on Australian sport in general.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] While scratch matches were played by Australian "diggers" in remote locations around the world, the game lost many of its great players to wartime service.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Some clubs and competitions never fully recovered.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Between 1914 and 1915, a proposed hybrid code of Australian football and rugby league, the predominant code of football in New South Wales and Queensland, was trialled without success.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In Queensland, the state league went into recess for the duration of the war.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] VFL club University left the league and went into recess due to severe casualties.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The West Australian Football League (WAFL) lost two clubs and the SANFL was suspended for one year in 1916 due to heavy club losses.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The Anzac Day match, the annual game between Essendon and Collingwood on Anzac Day, is one example of how the war continues to be remembered in the football community.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The role of the Australian National Football Council (ANFC) was primarily to govern the game at a national level and to facilitate interstate representative and club competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1968, the ANFC revived the Championship of Australia, a competition first held in 1888 between the premiers of the VFA and SAFA.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Although clubs from other states were at times invited, the final was almost always between the premiers from the two strongest state competitions of the time—South Australia and Victoria—with Adelaide hosting most of the matches at the request of the SAFA/SANFL.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The last match took place in 1976, with North Adelaide being the last non-Victorian winner in 1972.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Between 1976 and 1987, the ANFC, and later the Australian Football Championships (AFC) ran a night series, which invited clubs and representative sides from around the country to participate in a knock-out tournament parallel to the premiership seasons, which Victorian sides still dominated.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] With the lack of international competition, state representative matches were regarded with great importance.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Due in part to the VFL poaching talent from other states, Victoria dominated interstate matches for three-quarters of a century.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] State of Origin rules, introduced in 1977, stipulated that rather than representing the state of their adopted club, players would return to play for the state they were first recruited in.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This instantly broke Victoria's stranglehold over state titles and Western Australia and South Australia began to win more of their games against Victoria.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Both New South Wales and Tasmania scored surprise victories at home against Victoria in 1990.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The term "Barassi Line", named after VFL star Ron Barassi, was coined by scholar Ian Turner in 1978 to describe the "fictitious geographical barrier" separating the rugby-following parts of New South Wales and Queensland from the rest of the country, where Australian football reigned.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It became a reference point for the expansion of Australian football and for establishing a national league.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The way the game was played had changed dramatically due to innovative coaching tactics, with the phasing out of many of the game's kicking styles and the increasing use of handball; while presentation was influenced by television.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1982, in a move that heralded big changes within the sport, one of the original VFL clubs, South Melbourne, relocated to Sydney and became known as the Sydney Swans.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the late 1980s, due to the poor financial standing of many of the Victorian clubs, and a similar situation existing in Western Australia in the sport, the VFL pursued a more national competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Two more non-Victorian clubs, West Coast and Brisbane, joined the league in 1987 generating more than $8 million in license revenue for the Victorian clubs and increasing broadcast revenues which helped the Victorian clubs survive.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In their early years, the Sydney and Brisbane clubs struggled both on and off-field because the substantial TV revenues they generated by playing on a Sunday went to the VFL.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] To protect these revenues the VFL granted significant draft concessions and financial aid to keep the expansion clubs competitive.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The VFL changed its name to the Australian Football League (AFL) for the 1990 season, and over the next decade, three non-Victorian clubs gained entry: Adelaide (1991), Fremantle (1995) and the SANFL's Port Adelaide (1997), the only pre-existing club outside Victoria to join the league.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 2011 and 2012, respectively, two new non-Victorian clubs were added to the competition: Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The AFL, currently with 18 member clubs, is the sport's elite competition and most powerful body.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Following the emergence of the AFL, state leagues were quickly relegated to a second-tier status.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The VFA merged with the former VFL reserves competition in 1998, adopting the VFL name.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] State of Origin also declined in importance, especially after an increasing number of player withdrawals.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The AFL turned its focus to the annual International Rules Series against Ireland in 1998 before abolishing State of Origin the following year.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] State and territorial leagues still contest interstate matches, as do AFL Women players.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the 2010s, the AFL signalled further attempts at expanding into markets outside Australian football's traditional heartlands by hosting home-and-away matches in New Zealand, followed by China.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] After several failed bids since the early 1990s for a Tasmania-based AFL team, the Tasmania Football Club secured the 19th AFL license in 2023, and is set to compete by 2028.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In a standard match, a team may consist of anywhere between 14 and 18 players who may be permitted on the playing surface at any given time.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Each team may have up to four interchange (reserve) players who may be swapped for those on the field at any time during the game, although some leagues in less populated areas may use as few as 12 players.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In addition, some leagues, notably including the AFL, have each team designate one additional player as a substitute who can be used to make a single permanent exchange of players during a game for either medical or tactical reasons.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Players on the playing surface can be swapped with those on the interchange bench at any time.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] They must though pass through a designated "Interchange Area".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the event a player fails to pass through this area correctly, or if too many players from one team are found to be on the ground at a time, a free kick will be awarded to the opposing side.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Players may wear certain pieces of protective equipment, such as helmets or arm guards, if approved by the relevant controlling body.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Mouthguards are strongly recommended for all players.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Players are not permitted to wear jewellery, or other materials which the field umpire has deemed to be either potentially dangerous or increase the risk of injury to other players.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian rules football is played with an ellipsoid ball, between 72 and 73 cm (28 and 29 in) in long circumference, and 54.5 and 55.5 cm (21.5 and 21.9 in) in short circumference.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] For women's competitions, a smaller ball size of 69 and 53 cm (27 and 21 in) is used.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The ball must be inflated to a pressure of 69 kilopascals (10.0 pounds per square inch).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There are no defined laws regarding what material a ball must be made from, but standard AFL match-used balls are produced by Sherrin using cowhide leather.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] While there is no standard colour of the ball, red and yellow are most common and the only colours used at AFL level.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Yellow is used for games beginning after 3 pm or in an enclosed stadium, due to its greater visibility, and to assist score reviews.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Unlike other forms of football which are played on rectangular fields, Australian rules football playing fields are oval-shaped, and are between 135 and 185 metres (148 and 202 yd) long and 110 and 155 metres (120 and 170 yd) wide.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] At either end of the field, two sets of posts are erected in a straight line to indicate the scoring areas on the field, each with two kinds of posts, named the goal posts and the behind posts respectively.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The goal posts are placed first, located 6.4 metres (7.0 yd) apart from each other, with a behind post being placed a further 6.4 metres to the side of each goal post.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The name for the field line between two goal posts is known as the Goal Line.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Around the perimeter of the field, two white lines are drawn between the set of behind posts in an arc-shape, marking the field of play.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The 50m arcs, centre square, centre circle and goal square are used at the beginning of each quarter or after each goal.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Each team is permitted a maximum of six players in each 50m arc, with one in the goal square and four players in the centre square with one in the centre circle.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If this is breached, a free kick is awarded.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A game lasts for 80 minutes, split into four quarters consisting of 20 minutes playing time, with the clock being stopped for stoppages in play such as scores, or at the umpire's discretion, e.g. for serious injury.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Leagues may choose to employ shorter quarters of play at their discretion, such as the AFLW using 17 minutes per quarter.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] For any given match, two timekeepers are appointed to officiate the duration.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The timekeepers record all relevant statistics for the match, such as total quarter duration and score by each team.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Additionally timekeepers are required to sound a siren prior to and at the conclusion of each quarter until such time they are acknowledged by the field umpires.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] To stop and recommence the clock, the field umpires are required to signal to the timekeepers to indicate when the clock should be stopped or restarted.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Between each quarter, a break is observed to allow players a rest period.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Two six-minute breaks are observed between the first and second quarters, and the third and fourth quarters.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A longer 20-minute break is observed between the second and third quarter, commonly known as *half-time*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Each game is officiated by at least five match officials, known as an umpire.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] At AFL level, a video score review system is utilised.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Only umpires are permitted to request a review, and only scoring shots and potential scoring shots are permitted to be reviewed.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] An Australian rules football may only be propelled forward in a select few ways as defined by the Laws of Australian Football, published by the AFL.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The ball can be propelled in any direction by way of a kick or a clenched fist (called a handball)—deemed a correct disposal.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Failure to dispose of the ball in one of these two methods will result in a free kick to the opposing team.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If the ball is not currently in a player's possession, it can be moved legally through the usage of other means, such as punching.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] While in possession of the ball, players may run with the ball, but are required to either bounce or touch the ball on the ground at least once every 15 metres (16 yd).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Tackling is a technique employed by players used to force opposition players to dispose of the ball when they are in possession.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Failure to dispose of the ball when legally tackled may see the player penalised for 'holding the ball', except if the umpire deems there was a lack of prior opportunity to do so.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The ball carrier may only be tackled between the shoulders and knees from the front or side.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If the player forcefully contacts the opposing in the back while performing a tackle, the opposition player will be penalised for a push in the back.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If the opposition tackles the player with possession below the knees (a *low tackle* or a *trip*) or above the shoulders (a *high tackle*), the team with possession of the football gets a free kick.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Furthermore, tackles deemed to be dangerous by the umpire and those conducted from front-on while an opposition player has their head over the football are deemed to be prohibited contact, and will incur a free kick against the offending player.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Additionally, players may perform a technique known shepherding when the ball is within 5 metres (5.5 yd) of an opposition player.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Shepherding involves the use of a player's body to push, bump or otherwise block an opposition player, providing they do not have possession of the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If a player takes possession of the ball that has travelled more than 15 metres (16 yd) from another player's kick, by way of a catch within the field of play, it is deemed as a *mark*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] To be awarded a mark, it must be deemed that the player sufficiently controlled the ball and took possession prior to it being touched, touching the ground, or in the case of a contest, being spoiled by an opponent.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Upon a mark being taken, one opposition player may choose to stand on the point on the field where the mark was taken, known as "the mark".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] When a mark is taken, a small protected zone is established on the field, extending 10 metres (11 yd) either side of "the mark" and the player who marked the ball, with a small protected corridor between "the mark" and the player.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The opposition player is permitted to jump, but is not allowed to move from their position on "the mark".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Any other movements result in a distance penalty (50 metres in the AFL).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The player who was awarded the mark may then choose to either dispose of the ball over "the mark" or may choose to attempt disposal via a different method, in which case the field umpire will call "play on"—a verbal instruction to continue play.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] "Play on" may also be called if the umpire deems the player awarded the mark to be taking an unreasonable amount of time to dispose of the football.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Once the player has disposed of the ball, or "play on" is called, normal play resumes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Rucking is the only specialist skill and is performed by a ruck, the term for designated players from each side to which the umpire sends the ball to commence play.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Only a nominated ruck may contest ball-ups and throw-ins.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] They are the only player allowed within the 10 metre circle at a centre bounce.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Functionally the role is analogous to a basketball centre and as such rucks are typically the tallest player on the team.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Lifting teammates is not allowed so the ruck may only jump to reach the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If the ruck does not take possession of the football, it must be tapped or fisted, which is known as a hit-out.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] An effective hit-out that passes the ball to a teammate is known as a hit-out to advantage.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the event a player breaks a rule, a free kick is awarded to the opposing team, from the location that the misconduct occurred, or the ball's current location—whichever is closer to the team's scoring zone.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] As when a mark is taken, this location is called "the mark", and the same protections regarding the space apply.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the event a player engages in unsportsmanlike conduct after a free kick has been awarded or a mark has been paid to the opposing team, the umpire may instead award a 50-metre penalty.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] When imposed, the field umpire will advance "the mark" an additional 50 metres (55 yd) down the field or to the goal line, whichever is closer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Additional 50-metre penalties may be awarded if the behaviour continues after the initial penalty.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The laws of the game allow umpires to send off players for egregious foul play, although this law does not apply to the AFL and is largely only used at the local level.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There are two types of scoring shots in Australian football: goals and behinds.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A *goal* is worth six points, and is scored when the football is propelled between the goal posts and across the goal line at any height by way of a kick from the attacking team.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It may touch the ground, but must not have been touched by any player from either team or a goalpost prior to crossing the goal line.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A behind is also awarded to the team if the ball touches any part of an opposition player, including a foot, before passing across their goal or behind line.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] A free kick is awarded against any player who is deemed to have deliberately rushed a behind.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The team that has scored the most points at the end of play wins the game.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] If the scores are level on points at the end of play, then the game is a draw; extra time applies only during finals matches in some competitions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] As an example of a score report, consider a match between Sydney and Geelong with the former as the home team.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Sydney's score of 17 goals and 5 behinds equates to 107 points.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Geelong's score of 10 goals and 17 behinds equates to a 77-point tally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Sydney wins the match by a margin of 30 points.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] "Sydney, seventeen-five, one hundred and seven, defeated Geelong, ten-seventeen, seventy-seven".
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The home team is typically listed first and the visiting side is listed second.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The football season proper is from March to August (early autumn to late winter in Australia), with finals being held in September and October.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the tropics, the game is sometimes played in the wet season (October to March).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The AFL is recognised by the Australian Sports Commission as being the National Sporting Organisation for Australian rules.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There are also seven state/territory-based organisations in Australia, all of which are affiliated with the AFL.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] These state leagues hold annual semi-professional club competitions, with some also overseeing more than one league.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Local semi-professional or amateur organisations and competitions are often affiliated to their state organisations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 2003, the AFL became the *de facto* world governing body for Australian football when it pushed for the closure of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] There are also a number of affiliated organisations governing amateur clubs and competitions around the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In Australian football club competitions, the aim is to win the premiership (also known as the "flag"), which is typically decided by a finals series.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The teams that occupy the highest positions on the ladder after the home-and-away season play-off in a "semi-knockout" finals series, culminating in a single Grand Final match to determine the premiers.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Between four and eight teams contest a finals series, typically using the AFL final eight system or a variation of the McIntyre system.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The team which finishes first on the ladder after the home-and-away season is referred to as the "minor premier", but this usually holds little stand-alone significance, other than receiving a better draw in the finals.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Some metropolitan leagues have several tiered divisions, with promotion of the lower division premiers and relegation of the upper division's last placed team at the end of each year.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The high level of interest shown by women in Australian football is considered unique among the world's football codes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It was the case in the 19th century, as it is in modern times, that women made up approximately half of total attendances at Australian football matches—a far greater proportion than, for example, the estimated 10 per cent of women that comprise British soccer crowds.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This has been attributed in part to the egalitarian character of Australian football's early years in public parks where women could mingle freely and support the game in various ways.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In terms of participation, there are occasional 19th-century references to women playing the sport, but it was not until the 1910s that the first organised women's teams and competitions appeared.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Women's state leagues emerged in the 1980s, and in 2013, the AFL announced plans to establish a national semi-professional women's competition.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Amidst a surge in viewing interest and participation in women's football, the AFL pushed the founding date of the competition, named AFL Women's (AFLW), to 2017.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Eight AFL clubs won licences to field sides in its inaugural season.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] By 2022, all 18 clubs fielded an AFLW side, and there will be 19 teams with the admission of Tasmania to the competition in 2028.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Many related games have emerged from Australian football, mainly with variations of contact to encourage greater participation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] These include Auskick (played by children aged between 5 and 12), kick-to-kick (and its variants end-to-end footy and marks up), rec footy, 9-a-side footy, masters Australian football, handball and longest-kick competitions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Players outside Australia sometimes engage in related games adapted to available fields, like metro footy (played on gridiron fields) and Samoa rules (played on rugby fields).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] One such prominent example in use since 2018 is AFLX, a shortened variation of the game with seven players a side, played on a soccer-sized pitch.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The similarities between Australian football and the Irish sport of Gaelic football have allowed for the creation of a hybrid code known as international rules football.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The first international rules matches were contested in Ireland during the 1967 Australian Football World Tour.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Since then, various sets of compromise rules have been trialed, and in 1984 the International Rules Series commenced with national representative sides selected by Australia's state leagues (later by the AFL) and the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA).
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The competition became an annual event in 1998, but was postponed indefinitely in 2007 when the GAA pulled out due to Australia's severe and aggressive style of play.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] It resumed in Australia in 2008 under new rules to protect the player with the ball.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] During the colonial period, Australian rules was sometimes referred to as Australasian rules, reflecting its popularity in New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game was played outside Australasia as early as 1888 when Australians studying at Edinburgh University and London University formed teams and competed in London.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Further international exposure came that same year, when the first British rugby side to tour the Southern Hemisphere played Australian rules matches in both Australia and New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] By the early 20th century, it had spread with the Australian diaspora to South Africa, the United States and other parts of the Anglosphere; however this growth went into rapid decline during and after World War I, leading also to a decades long hiatus in New Zealand.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] After World War II, it experienced growth in the Pacific region, particularly in Papua New Guinea and Nauru, where it is now the national sport.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Today, the sport is played at an amateur level in various countries throughout the world.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Twenty-three countries have participated in the International Cup, which was held triennially in Australia from 2002 to 2017.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] International competition resumed in 2024 with three regional tournaments: the Transatlantic Cup, Asia Cup, and Pacific Cup.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Nine countries have also participated in the AFL Europe Championship.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 2013, participation across AFL Europe's 21 member nations was more than 5,000 players, the majority of which are European nationals rather than Australian expats.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The sport also has a growing presence in India.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Over 20 countries have either affiliation or working agreements with the AFL.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Most present-day international amateur clubs and leagues are based in North America, Europe and Asia, with the oldest typically having originated in the 1980s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] That decade, the sport developed a cult following in the United States when matches were broadcast on the fledgling ESPN network.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Growing international interest has been assisted by exhibition matches, players switching between football codes, and Australia's multicultural makeup.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Many VFL/AFL players were born overseas, with a growing number recruited through various initiatives.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] One notable example is the Irish experiment, which, since the 1980s, has seen many Gaelic footballers leave the amateur GAA to play Australian rules professionally.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This has expanded to women's football, with 39 Irish players on AFLW lists for the 2025 season.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Although Australian rules football is not an Olympic sport, it was showcased at the MCG as part of the 1956 Summer Olympics, held in Melbourne.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In addition, when Brisbane hosted the 1982 Commonwealth Games, an exhibition match between Richmond and Carlton was held at the Gabba.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian football has attracted more overall interest among Australians than any other football code.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The 2024 AFL season saw an average attendance of 38,344 fans per match, making the AFL Australia's, and one of the world's best-attended sports leagues.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Also that year, data indicated 1,319,687 people, or 1 in 20 Australians, are members of an AFL club.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The most-visited sports website in Australia in 2023 was the AFL's, attracting 1.89 billion total visits.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Approximately 40% of Australians aged 14+ watch AFL matches on TV either occasionally or regularly.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The 2024 AFL Grand Final was that year's highest-rating free-to-air television broadcast in Australia, with an in-home audience of 4 million watching Seven's coverage; overall TV viewership reached at least 7,569,000.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The AFL's current TV broadcasting rights deal with Seven and Foxtel is worth an Australian record $4.5 billion.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In terms of participation, there were at least 581,000 registered players in Australia in 2024.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] This figure encompasses community football at junior, youth, and senior levels, as well as programs such as Footy 9s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Among Australian children aged 0–14, it is the fifth most common sporting activity, behind swimming, soccer, basketball and gymnastics.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Women and girls account for 20% of all community football registrations.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian football has inspired works by many writers and poets, including C.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Dennis, Helen Garner, Peter Goldsworthy and Kerry Greenwood.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Historians Manning Clarke and Geoffrey Blainey have also written extensively on the sport.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Slang within Australian football has impacted Australian English more broadly, with a number of expressions taking on new meanings in non-sporting contexts, e.g., to "get a guernsey" is to gain recognition or approval, while "shirt-fronting" someone is to accost them.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In 1889, Australian impressionist painter Arthur Streeton captured football games *en plein air* for the 9 by 5 Impression Exhibition, titling one work *The National Game*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Paintings by Sidney Nolan (*Footballer*, 1946) and John Brack (*Three of the Players*, 1953) helped to establish Australian football as a serious subject for modernists, and many Aboriginal artists have explored the game, often fusing it with the mythology of their region.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Vincent Namatjira won the 2020 Archibald Prize for his portrait of Adam Goodes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In cartooning, WEG's VFL/AFL premiership posters—inaugurated in 1954—have achieved iconic status among Australian football fans.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Australian football statues can be found throughout the country, some based on famous photographs, among them Haydn Bunton Sr.'s leap, Jack Dyer's charge and Nicky Winmar lifting his jumper.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In the 1980s, a group of postmodern architects based in Melbourne began incorporating references to Australian football into their buildings, an example being Building 8 by Edmond and Corrigan.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Dance sequences based on Australian football feature heavily in Robert Helpmann's 1964 ballet *The Display*, his first and most famous work for the Australian Ballet.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] The game has also inspired well-known plays such as *And the Big Men Fly* (1963) by Alan Hopgood and David Williamson's *The Club* (1977), which was adapted into a 1980 film, directed by Bruce Beresford.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Mike Brady's 1979 hit "Up There Cazaly" is considered an Australian football anthem, and references to the sport can be found in works by popular musicians, from singer-songwriter Paul Kelly to the alternative rock band TISM.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Others, such as Tame Impala's Kevin Parker, have written songs for their favourite AFL club.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Many Australian football video games have been released, notably the AFL series.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] For the centenary of the VFL/AFL in 1996, the Australian Football Hall of Fame was established.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] That year, 136 significant figures across the various competitions were inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Each years since the creation of the Hall of Fame, a panel selects a small group of players they deem worthy for this prestigious honour, resulting in a total number of more than 300 inductees as of 2024.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] In addition to the Hall of Fame, select members are chosen to receive the elite *Legend* status.
[src:braybrook-victoria/australian-rules] Due to restrictions limiting the number of Legend status players to 10% of the total number of Hall of Fame inductees, there are currently only 32 players with the status in the Hall of Fame as of 2024.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Avondale Heights is located on a plateau bounded by a large bend of the Maribyrnong River to the east, south, and west, and to the north by Buckley Street.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The suburb derives its name from the *Avondale Estate*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Originally known as *Maribyrnong West*, when the Council undertook to change the name, postal authorities drew attention to the existence of Avondale in Queensland.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The suburb was therefore called Avondale Heights to distinguish it from the Queensland town.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Mahony Griffin prepared plans for part of the area: Milleara Estate in the north (also known as City View) in the 1920s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] One objective of their design was to remake suburbia and society.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] They did this through creating internal gardens where communities could both physically and socially bind together.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] They imagined children's playgrounds, social centres, nature reserves and links with an intricate system of pedestrian ways.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The streets are designed in a curvilinear way typical of Griffin's design, often following the topography of the land.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] There is only one main road – Military Road which runs from Canning Street and Maribyrnong Road, then becoming Milleara Road at the Avondale Heights Police Station.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] There are about 40 shops at the Canning Street end (including Raglan Street) and 20 at the other end, near the St Martin De Porres Primary School.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Prior to European colonisation of Melbourne, the Wurundjeri Aboriginal people of the Kulin nation moved through the area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Evidence has been found of human occupation for at least 18,000 years.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] On 10 October 1940, James White dug up an ancient human skull (now known as the Keilor Cranium) on the banks of the Maribyrnong River.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] This skull has been found to be between 8,000 and 15,800 years old.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] In 1803 Charles Grimes, the New South Wales Surveyor General, sailed up the Yarra River in the *Buffalo* and sent a rowing boat to explore the 'Saltwater River', as the Maribyrnong was then called.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The rowing boat reached a rocky, shallow area now known as *Solomon's Ford*, and could go no further.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] In 1835 with the initial settlement of Melbourne, Edmund Davis Fergusson and Michael Solomon established a pastoral holding in the Avondale-Sunshine area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] On Solomon's sheep station the ford, now at the west end of Canning Street, soon became known as *Solomon's Ford*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] This was the lowest crossing point on the Saltwater (Maribyrnong) River, and was for many years the only overland route from Melbourne to Geelong and further west.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The MMBW reconstructed the ford and the riverbanks nearby in the 1980s, adding large basalt boulders to form stepping stones across the river.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Today this ford is one of the last remaining fords in the Melbourne metropolitan area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] During World War I the Canning Street bridge was known as Cordite Bridge as it led to the Department of Defence Explosives Factory.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] A password was necessary to cross the bridge during the war.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] During World War II a night curfew was imposed on the river and a boom was put into place to hinder access.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Tourists from Melbourne were attracted to the area with the construction of the elaborate and popular Riverview Tea Gardens in 1909.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] These grew to include sportsgrounds, kiosks, a dance hall and aviaries.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Guests stopped here on their pleasure cruises, and the venue reached the height of its popularity in the 1920s-1930s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The Tea Gardens were closed during World War II and fell into disrepair.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Nothing of them remains today, but the riverfront area is still used for recreation, having become Tea Gardens Reserve.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] During the 1930s the district was subdivided into small dairy and cattle farms, with some poultry farming.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Even into the 1960s market gardens and small dairy farms operated in the area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] In the late 1960s housing development changed the area into a residential suburb with views of Melbourne city from the plateau.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] The Avondale Heights Post Office opened on 9 December 1957 as the suburb developed (A Maribyrnong West office had been open between 1943 and 1947).
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] It was announced in 2008 that Avondale Heights was set to experience its largest urbanisation initiative since the formation of the area as a suburb.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] This was due to the sale of the old Kangan Batman TAFE site to private investors, to develop medium density housing.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] On 26 May 2015, Moonee Valley City Council issued a planning permit for 135 new homes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] Cyclists and walkers have easy access to the Maribyrnong River Trail along the Maribyrnong River.
[src:braybrook-victoria/avondale-heights-victoria] There is no tram route through Avondale Heights - the closest is the route 57 tram which ends in Maribyrnong.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] Ballarat Road commences at the interchange with Western Freeway at Ravenhall and continues in a south-easterly direction as a four-lane, dual-carriageway road through the suburbs of Deer Park, where it meets with Western Ring Road in Ardeer.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] It continues in an easterly direction to Maidstone, where it narrows to a four-lane, single carriageway road, and continues in a south-easterly direction to Footscray, where it widens again to a dual-carriageway road at the intersection with Geelong Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] It continues east before crossing the Maribyrnong River over Lynchs Bridge, where it changes name to Smithfield Road (and continues onto Flemington).
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] VicRoads' declaration states Ballarat Road ends at the intersection with Geelong Road, however signposts still indicate the road ends at Lynch's Bridge across the Maribyrnong.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] **(Main) Ballarat Road**, from Melton via Braybrook to Melton, was declared a Main Road on 30 December 1913.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] The passing of the *Highways and Vehicles Act 1924* provided for the declaration of State Highways, roads two-thirds financed by the state government through the Country Roads Board.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] **Western Highway** was declared a State Highway on 1 July 1925,cobbled from a collection of roads from Melbourne through to Ballarat, subsuming the original declaration of Main Ballarat Road as a Main Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] The Whitlam government introduced the federal *National Roads Act 1974*, where roads declared as a National Highway were still the responsibility of the states for road construction and maintenance, but were fully compensated by the federal government for money spent on approved projects.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] As an important interstate link between the capitals of Victoria and South Australia, Western Highway was declared a National Highway in 1974.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] This section of the road was eventually bypassed as the main route through western Melbourne when Deer Park bypass opened in 2009, with the road name devolving back to its original identity as Ballarat Road as a consequence; the route is still co-signed as Western Highway on older signs however.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] As part of Western Highway, the road was signed as National Route 8 in 1955, then as National Highway 8 when upgraded to a National Highway in 1974.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] Once the Deer Park bypass was opened in 2009 and National Route M8 was re-routed onto the new bypass, the old route was replaced with Metropolitan Route 8 from Ravenhall to the inner suburb of Footscray.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] Tram route 82 runs along the Footscray section of Ballarat Road, between Gordon & Droop Streets.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] The Serviceton railway line from Southern Cross runs parallel to Ballarat Road from Sunshine about 1 km to the south, with stations at Albion, and Deer Park.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] Several bus routes run along Ballarat Road at various points (routes 215, 216, 220, 223, 256, 400, 406, 408, 410 and 456) with 456 continuing on the Western Freeway to Melton.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] With three lanes running in each direction, between Deer Park and the Western Ring Road, this was one of the worst bottlenecks in western Melbourne with traffic reaching 70,000 vehicles per day, with 10 per cent of this consisting of heavy vehicles.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] This caused delays, in part due to seven traffic signals between the Western Ring Road and the start of the Western Freeway.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] With the completion of the Deer Park Bypass traffic volumes were predicted to decrease to local traffic standard since its opening on 5 April 2009.
[src:braybrook-victoria/ballarat-road-melbourne] In central Melbourne, Ballarat Road has a single carriageway from Braybrook and is a two lane arterial road, including one small stretch which shares the road with trams.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] A **commuter town** is a populated area that is primarily residential rather than commercial or industrial.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Routine travel from home to work and back is called commuting, which is where the term comes from.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] A commuter town may be called by many other terms: "**bedroom community**" (Canada and northeastern US), "**bedroom town**", "**bedroom suburb**" (US), "**dormitory town**" (UK).
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] The term "exurb" was used from the 1950s, but since 2006, is generally used for areas beyond suburbs and specifically areas less densely built than the suburbs to which the residents of exurbs commute.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Commuter towns may form when workers in a region cannot afford to live where they work and must seek residency in another town with a lower cost of living.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] The late 20th century, the dot-com bubble and United States housing bubble drove housing costs in Californian metropolitan areas to historic highs, spawning exurban growth in adjacent counties.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Workers with jobs in San Francisco found themselves moving further and further away to nearby cities like Oakland, Burlingame, and San Mateo.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] As rental and housing costs kept increasing, even renters that would normally be considered affluent elsewhere would struggle with the prospect of home ownership in an area with higher quality schools and amenities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] As of 2003, over 80% of the workforce of Tracy, California, was employed in the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Other commuter towns are formed with the intention of the municipality focusing on residential areas and limiting commercial development, to attract families who want to establish long-term communities and/or minimize perceived problems with commercial development.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Atherton, California is one such example.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] In some cases, commuter towns can result from changing economic conditions.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Steubenville, Ohio along with neighboring Weirton, West Virginia had an independent regional identity until the collapse of the steel industry in the 1980s.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Steubenville Pike and the Parkway West also created easier access to the much larger city of Pittsburgh.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] In 2013, Jefferson County, Ohio (where Steubenville is located) was added to the Pittsburgh metropolitan area as part of its larger Combined Statistical Area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] In Japan, most of the national railway network was privatized by the 1980s but unlike in the UK, both the national railway's tracks, trains, stations and real estate were included in the privatization agreements.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Japan's privately operated railroads view real estate investment and development of commuter towns as central to their business model.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] These railroads continuously develop new residential and commercial areas alongside their existing and new routes and stations and adjust their train schedules in order to provide existing and prospective commuters with convenient work-commute routines.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] This is quite different from North American commuter towns which are almost exclusively the result of transportation by car.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Where commuters are wealthier and small town housing markets are weaker than city housing markets, the development of a bedroom community may raise local housing prices and attract upscale service businesses in a process akin to gentrification.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Long-time residents may be displaced by new commuter residents due to rising house prices.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] This can also be influenced by zoning restrictions in urbanized areas that prevent the construction of suitably cheap housing closer to places of employment.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] The number of commuter towns increased in the US and the UK during the 20th century because of a trend for people to move out of the cities into the surrounding green belt.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] In the United States, it is common for commuter towns to create disparities in municipal tax rates.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] When a commuter town collects few business taxes, residents must pay the brunt of the public operating budget in higher property or income taxes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Such municipalities may scramble to encourage commercial growth once an established residential base has been reached.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] In the UK, commuter towns were developed by railway companies to create demand for their lines.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] One 1920s pioneer of this form of development was the Metropolitan Railway (now part of London Underground) which marketed its Metro-land developments.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] This initiative encouraged many to move out of central and inner-city London to suburbs such as Harrow, or out of London itself, to commuter villages in Buckinghamshire or Hertfordshire.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Commuter towns have more recently been built ahead of adequate transportation infrastructure, thus spurring the development of roads and public transportation systems.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] These can take the form of light rail lines extending from the city center to new streetcar suburbs and new or expanded highways, whose construction and traffic can lead to the community becoming part of a larger conurbation.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] A 2014 study by the British Office for National Statistics found that commuting also affects wellbeing.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Commuters are more likely to be anxious, dissatisfied and have the sense that their daily activities lack meaning than those who don't have to travel to work, even if they are paid more.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] The term *exurb* (a portmanteau of "extra & urban") was coined by Auguste Comte Spectorsky in his 1955 book *The Exurbanites*, to describe the ring of prosperous communities beyond the suburbs that are commuter towns for an urban area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] However, since a landmark report by the Brookings Institution in 2006, the term is generally used for areas beyond suburbs and specifically less densely built than the suburbs to which the exurbs' residents commute.
[src:braybrook-victoria/bedroom-community] Comparatively low density towns – often featuring large lots and large homes – create heavy motor vehicle dependency.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook is bounded in the west by Duke Street, in the north by the Maribyrnong River, in the east by Ashley Street, and in the south by the Sunbury railway line and Sunshine Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook Post Office opened on 1 December 1860.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook was primarily an industrial suburb.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Today it is composed of a mix of residential and light industrial.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Historically this is due to stigma, but the western suburbs are expanding now due to prime location and rising fuel prices.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Some gentrification has occurred in the past decade with many former factory sites developed for modern housing projects (townhouses etc.).
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] More and more first home buyers and developers are focusing on Braybrook and neighbouring Maidstone and West Footscray, but traces of its industrial past may be still evident.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook has been ranked 95 out of top 314 most liveable suburbs in Melbourne in the "2011 Liveability Stakes" by *The Age* and *The Melbourne Magazine*.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The suburb has produced a number of famous sporting and show business personalities.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] 1960s pop singer Yvonne Barrett resided with her family in Dodds Street.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Barrett was murdered in 1985, with her funeral service held at Braybrook's Christ The King Catholic church in Churchill Avenue.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] 1970's Pop sensation Jamie Redfern also lived in the area.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Ray "Screamy" Eames, the drummer from popular Melbourne pub-rock act The Blue Echoes lived in Braybrook.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] High-profile Australian rules footballers Doug Hawkins, Ted Whitten and Brian Wilson played for the Braybrook Football Club.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The area is served by rail, with Tottenham and Sunshine the closest railway stations to Braybrook.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The Braybrook Community Centre is located at 107–139 Churchill Avenue, Braybrook.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The centre offers children's facilities, crafts, English as a second language (ESL) classes, computer and Internet facilities, playgroups, health and wellbeing classes and financial counselling.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] It also offers rooms and halls for hire.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Cohealth is housed within the centre and offers general medical practitioners, optometry, physiotherapy, podiatry, social work, occupational therapists, speech pathology for children, pharmaceutical program and a women's and children's health nurse.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The Community Hub at 19 Hargreaves Crescent is a base for the Neighbourhood Renewal Team and the Braybrook and Maidstone Neighbourhood Association to collaborate with local residents to bring about change.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Local residents are welcome to visit and learn more about Neighbourhood Renewal and the Association.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The Hub will be home to the Braidstone Bulletin – a local community newsletter and will have small meeting rooms available for local groups.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The Catholic parish of Christ the King, Braybrook was established in 1952, from sections of Sunshine and West Footscray parishes.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] In 1958, the parish transferred from its temporary centre in Rupert Street to its present location on 65–67 Churchill Avenue, with the opening of the Catholic Centre.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] There is a local shopping centre called Central West Plaza, located on the corner of Ashley Street and South Road on the border of West Footscray.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] It was built on the grounds of a former RAAF base and the shopping centre has a general aviation theme, including a WW2 Vampire fighter plane on display at the Ashley Street entrance.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] This was moved from the office complex development adjacent in 2003.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] There is another major shopping centre on the corner of Ashley Street and Ballarat Road, Braybrook Shopping Centre.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] It has 24 hour Derrimut Gym and Rabbit Hole Kids playcentre.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] KFL supermarket recently took over Woolworths whom left in 2021.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Most retail businesses in the area are still located in strip malls and small individual shops on Ballarat Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The strip malls are on South Road, Churchill Avenue and Ballarat Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] A large number of fast food restaurants are on the Braybrook section of Ballarat Road.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook is near Barkly Village, a section of Barkly Street in West Footscray that hosts many local and ethnic grocers, stores and a Sims Supermarket.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Australia's first Masters Home Improvement store was located on Ballarat Road, however it closed in 2016 when the chain went out of business.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] The site, since its opening in 2019, is a Home Consortium shopping centre, featuring a TK Maxx fashion outlet and a Coles supermarket.
[src:braybrook-victoria/braybrook-victoria] Braybrook Sporting Club has Australian Rules football teams competing in the Western Region Football League.
